>but that seems not fun to write.
All depends on how you write him. If he has a complete rod up his ass then yeah it'll get grating pretty quickly. The main question you have to ask is "Why is he a total wizard?".
As a example possible avenue, While he never had any issues being with with women of any kind in a general sense growing up or in his adult life, he was always so sucked into either his nerd hobbies or building up his shop later in life that the idea of "settling down" sounded absolutely dreadful, as it would mean having his existence sucked away by the relationship, as he saw with all his other friends over the years, as they slowly drifted apart due to "settling down". So he usually cuts potential relationships right in the bud as soon as they got to the bf/gf stage. Essentially eternally friend-zoning people. Which enough of the potential pool of women who would ever make it that far in the area being so small that by his early-mid 20's, he never really had another girlfriend again.
Play into him having nothing with her being a (former) stripper and such, but it takes real work to get him to a point where he's willing to have "that kind of relationship" again, showing that you don't have to loose yourself to it by way of the fact she's becoming less ditzy over time while not loosing what makes her 'her'.
Wow that became more of a story than I intended. Again, just a jumping off point for a train of thought, I have zero intention for any of that to be wholesale transplanted to a longer narrative.

Quoted By: >>30931209 >>30931653 >>30933275 >>30933611 >>30935959 >>30938294 >>30939718 >>30943848
Hey guys, Ago_ here with chapter 5 of "On the Fringes"!

https://pastebin.com/3NGXxFe1

>I started reading words at random. I felt like a fool, to be honest; a natural speaker's reaction to a non-native is usually to talk slowly, but I had always thought it was a useless gesture. Speaking English slowly to someone that did not understand English would not make things easier on them. Her issue was not one of understanding, however -- based on the ease with which she understood me, it was clear she had a good vocabulary. Her sole issue was vocalization. With a vastly different tongue and mouth, she would have to move them in slightly different ways to produce the same sounds as me. So for about the next hour, she just sat and watched -- maybe a little too close for comfort, not that I would say anything -- as I read from the dictionary. She asked me to repeat almost every word several times, not for lack of understanding but for getting a handle on what my mouth was doing. She would dissect each syllable into its component sounds, deconstructing difficult words piecemeal until she was able to string together each syllable almost as naturally as a native speaker.

Also, I edited the earlier bit about the wind-up clock into something more vague and less important, to show there was at that point, still some ambiguity to their communication with one another. Also I am not a speech pathologist, and the research I did was not all that helpful in helping me construct the start of this chapter.

As usual, I appreciate and read all comments and critiques, good or bad.

OK. Let me just say wow.

I was hoping after the first few parts you were going to get psychological on the reader. This might not mean much, but my degree was in biochemistry with a focus on neuropharmacology. To be damning about things, I think all four of the major characters (Jake, Charlotte, Helen and Rebecca) are lying in one form or another. You've painted a world that runs on information control and many other traits of our world and amped the problems up in a given direction.

Keep peeling the layers off these characters. Once the next big sabo hits the gearworks we're going to move closer to the big picture.
